docs.lead_paragraph: In the old Tory day, not many years back in England, there was a prevalent and popular belief, that gentlemen of the Press were all more or less tinctured with revolutionary, Jacobin, radical and infidel opinions, and he who happened to be seen even loitering round the precints of a newspaper office, was looked upon as unsafe and dangerous, "a fellow in fact, who thought."
